{"title_page": "Sonic Advance", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sonic Advance\n| image = Sonic Advance Coverart.png\n| alt = Cover art, depicting Sonic, Tails, Amy, Knuckles, and Chao. The game's logo is seen above all characters, and the Sega and Nintendo logos are seen in the right and left hand corners, respectively.\n| developer = [[Dimps]]<br/>[[Sonic Team]]\n| publisher = {{vgrelease|JP|[[Sega]]|NA|[[THQ]]|EU|[[Infogrames]]}}\n| series = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| platforms = [[Game Boy Advance]], [[N-Gage (device)|{{nowrap|N-Gage}}]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Mobile phone]]\n| released = '''Game Boy Advance'''{{vgrelease|JP|December 20, 2001|NA|February 3, 2002|PAL|March 8, 2002}}'''N-Gage'''{{vgrelease|WW|October 7, 2003}}'''Android'''{{vgrelease|JP|November 25, 2011}}'''J2ME'''{{vgrelease|WW|2011}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]], [[action game|action]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| director = Akinori Nishiyama\n| producer = [[Yuji Naka]]<br/>Hiroshi Matsumoto\n| artist = [[Yuji Uekawa]]\n| composer = [[Tatsuyuki Maeda]]<br/>Yutaka Minobe\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Sonic Advance'''''|\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9|Sonikku Adobansu|known as '''''SonicN''''' on the [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]]|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 2001 [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game]] developed by [[Dimps]] for the [[Game Boy Advance]] (GBA). It was the first ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' game to be released on a [[Nintendo]] platform and was produced in commemoration of the series' tenth anniversary. The story follows [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]], [[Tails (character)|Tails]], [[Knuckles the Echidna|Knuckles]], and [[Amy Rose|Amy]] as they journey to stop [[Doctor Eggman]] from taking over the world. Controlling a character, players are tasked with completing each [[Level (video gaming)|level]], defeating Eggman and his [[robot]] army, and collecting the seven [[Chaos Emeralds]].\n\nDevelopment began after [[Sega]] shifted its focus to third-party software development, due to the poor performance of the [[Dreamcast]] console. Sega recruited [[Dimps]] to lead development, making the game the first in the franchise developed by the studio. While ''Sonic Advance'' follows a similar style of gameplay to the [[Sega Genesis]] ''Sonic'' games, certain concepts and designs were reused from newer titles such as ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998). The game has been [[Porting|ported]] to [[Nokia]]'s [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices, and is available on the [[Wii U]] via the [[Virtual Console]] in Japan.\n\n''Sonic Advance'' received positive reviews for its graphics, character animations, and its similarities to the original Genesis games, but was criticized for its short length and special stages. It was a major commercial success, selling 1.21 million copies in the United States and is among the [[List of best-selling Game Boy Advance video games|GBA's bestselling titles]]. Dimps has since created many entries in the series, including two sequels to the game, ''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' (2002) and ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' (2004).\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:SonicAdvanceLoop.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Screenshot showing Sonic running around a loop in Angel Island zone, the game's fifth level. The HUD on the upper left-hand corner shows the timer, score, and amount of rings the player has.|Gameplay screenshot showing [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] in one of the game's levels]]\n''Sonic Advance'' is a [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game|platformer]] [[action game]] reminiscent of the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' games released for the [[Sega Genesis]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Players journey through an island to defeat [[Doctor Eggman]], who is attempting to capture its animal population to turn them into evil [[robot]]s. Players select one of four characters, each with their own unique set of moves. [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]] is fastest and can perform an \"insta-shield\" that protects him for a moment; [[Tails (character)|Tails]] can fly or swim for a short time; [[Knuckles the Echidna]] can glide through the air, swim above water for a few seconds and climb walls; and [[Amy Rose]] can destroy enemies using a hammer.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> Except for Amy, each character can defeat enemy robots by jumping and curling into a ball, or by performing a spin dash on the ground to gain speed. By entering a [[cheat code]], players can control Sonic while Tails runs alongside him, similar to ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2]]'' (1992).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Sonic Advance + Sonic Adventure 2 Battle Official Perfect Guide|last=|first=|publisher=Versus Books|year=2002|isbn=9780970646866|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe game takes place over six [[level (video gaming)|level]]s called zones. Each zone is split into two acts, where the player must guide their selected character past enemies and obstacles such as spikes and bottomless pits to reach the end in under ten minutes. Scattered around acts are springboards, boost pads, and golden [[Rings (Sonic the Hedgehog)|rings]], which serve as a form of [[Health (gaming)|health]]; players survive hits as long as they have at least one ring, but their rings will scatter and disappear after a short period.<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Players collect canisters that contain [[power-up]]s such as speed shoes, elemental shields, and [[invincibility]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The first act ends when players pass a signpost, and the second culminates in a [[boss fight]] with Eggman; after hitting him eight times, Eggman will flee and drop a capsule of captured animals. Each character starts the game with a number of lives, which are lost when they are hit with no rings in their possession, crushed, drown, or fall in a bottomless pit. If all lives are lost, they will receive a [[game over]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" />\n\nSpecial springs can be found near the top of certain acts.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> By jumping on them, the player can reach a special stage, where they are sent down a tube to collect rings. If they collect enough rings, the player receives a [[Chaos Emerald]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Collecting all seven Emeralds unlocks an extra boss fight. The game also features a [[minigame]], Tiny Chao Garden, where players can raise [[Chao (Sonic)|Chao]].<ref name=\"nwrreview\" /> Players can transfer their Chao between the Tiny Chao Garden and the Chao Garden from the [[GameCube]] versions of ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' and ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]''.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> The game also features a competitive [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] mode, where up to four owners of the game can race to the end of a level or search for Chao.<ref name=\"nwrreview\" />\n\n==Development and release==\n[[File:Nintendo-Game-Boy-Advance-Purple-FL.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An indigo-colored Game Boy Advance (GBA), the handheld device Sonic Advance was developed for.|''Sonic Advance'' was developed for [[Nintendo]]'s [[Game Boy Advance]] handheld console]]\nIn January 2001, [[Sega]], facing financial troubles with the underperformance of its [[Dreamcast]] console, shifted from first to third-party software publishing,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sega-announces-drastic-restructuring/1100-2680518/|title=Sega announces drastic restructuring|last1=Ahmed|first1=Shahed|date=January 31, 2001|website=GameSpot|publisher=CBS Interactive|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704153502/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sega-announces-drastic-restructuring/1100-2680518/|archive-date=July 4, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> with [[Sony Computer Entertainment]]'s [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Nintendo]]'s [[Game Boy Advance]] (GBA) being primary focuses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/24/sega-confirms-ps2-and-game-boy-advance-negotiations|title=Sega Confirms PS2 and Game Boy Advance Negotiations|author1=IGN Staff|first=January 23, 2001|date=|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323144955/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/24/sega-confirms-ps2-and-game-boy-advance-negotiations|archive-date=March 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> A team of developers was formed to begin development on ''Sonic the Hedgehog Advance'' (later renamed ''Sonic Advance''), a ''Sonic'' title for the GBA that would commemorate the series' 10th anniversary.<ref name=\"says\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5068/sega-says|title=Sega Says...|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=January 31, 2001|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816040211/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5068/sega-says|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5572/sonic-team-shows-its-goods|title=Sonic Team shows its goods!|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=February 8, 2001|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816035052/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5572/sonic-team-shows-its-goods|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> [[Dimps]], a studio formed by several former [[Neo Geo Pocket Color]] developers and funded by Sega, Sony, and [[Bandai]], developed the game with assistance from [[Sonic Team]].<ref name=\"igndimps\"/> Sonic Team conceived the game, but was understaffed on employees familiar with the GBA hardware and so recruited Dimps.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harris |first1=Craig |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/14/e3-2004-yuji-naka-talks-sonic |title=E3 2004: Yuji Naka Talks Sonic |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |date=May 13, 2004}}</ref> Several Dimps members worked on the critically acclaimed ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog Pocket Adventure]]'' (1999) for the Neo Geo Pocket Color.<ref name=\"igndimps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/04/18/gba-sonic-developed-by-dimps|title=GBA Sonic Developed By Dimps|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=April 18, 2001|website=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818082311/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/04/18/gba-sonic-developed-by-dimps|archive-date=August 18, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe developers decided to return to a gameplay style similar to the original Genesis ''Sonic'' games, which Naka felt was refreshing. Despite this, they also incorporated concepts from ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998) and [[Sonic Adventure 2|its 2001 sequel]], such as the ability to grind on rails and the modernized character designs by [[Yuji Uekawa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2001-first-impressions-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance/1100-2762273/|title=E3 2001: First Impressions: Sonic the Hedgehog Advance|last1=Ahmed|first1=Shahed|date=May 18, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923181118/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2001-first-impressions-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance/1100-2762273/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"allgame\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31757&tab=review|title=Sonic Advance - Review|last1=Miller|first1=Skyler|date=February 5, 2002|website=AllGame|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115083100/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31757&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|url-status=|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref> As the ''Sonic'' games released for the Dreamcast allowed players to download minigames onto the [[Visual Memory Unit]] (VMU), the development team decided to expand upon this by using a similar concept with the [[Nintendo GameCube \u2013 Game Boy Advance link cable|GameCube's GBA link cable]], making ''Sonic Advance'' one of the first games to use the cable.<ref name=\"tgs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tgs-2001-fall-sonic-advance-links-to-the-gamecube/1100-2817734/|title=TGS 2001 Fall: Sonic Advance links to the GameCube|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=October 15, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418103024/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/tgs-2001-fall-sonic-advance-links-to-the-gamecube/1100-2817734/|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> It also features graphical techniques such as rotation effects and [[Mode 7]].<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/>\n\nSega announced ''Sonic Advance'' and two other GBA titles on January 30, 2001.{{efn| The others were rereleases of ''[[ChuChu Rocket!]]'' (1999) and ''[[Puyo Puyo (video game)|Puyo Puyo]]'' (1991)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/31/sega-of-america-announces-three-for-game-boy-advance|title=Sega of America Announces Three for Game Boy Advance|author1=IGN Staff|first=|date=January 30, 2001|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809222222/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/31/sega-of-america-announces-three-for-game-boy-advance|archive-date=August 9, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> A video containing footage of the game's first level was featured at the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] (E3) in May 2001,<ref name=\"firstlook\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/05/18/e3-first-look-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance|title=E3: First Look: Sonic the Hedgehog Advance|author1=IGN Staff|first=May 18, 2001|date=|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818080300/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/05/18/e3-first-look-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance|archive-date=August 18, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> and [[game demo|demo]] versions were showcased at [[Nintendo Space World]] and the [[Tokyo Game Show]] later that year.<ref name=\"tgs\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/space-world-2001-hands-onsonic-advance/1100-2807904/|title=Space World 2001 Hands-on Sonic Advance|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=August 27, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923182155/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/space-world-2001-hands-onsonic-advance/1100-2807904/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> Sega released ''Sonic Advance'' in Japan on December 20, 2001,<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9|url=http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/gametitle/GameboyAdvance.html|website=Sonic Channel|trans-title=Game Boy Advance|publisher=Sega|accessdate=November 2, 2017|language=Japanese|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722111028/http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/gametitle/GameboyAdvance.html|archive-date=July 22, 2015|df=}}</ref> while [[THQ]] released it in North America on February 3, 2002. The game was released in Europe on March 8, 2003,<ref name=\"nwrreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/3858/sonic-advance-game-boy-advance|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=February 10, 2002|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816040942/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/3858/sonic-advance-game-boy-advance|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> where [[Infogrames]] handled marketing and distribution.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shannon |first1=Victoria |title=Infogrames Will Distribute Company's Games in Europe : Tech Brief:Sega Picks Partner |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/29/business/worldbusiness/IHT-infogrames-will-distribute-companys-games-in.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 18, 2019 |date=June 29, 2001}}</ref> A [[porting|port]] for [[Nokia]]'s [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]], ''SonicN'', was released worldwide on October 7, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=SonicN - N-Gage|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-the-hedgehog-1/nng-573371|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425185840/http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-the-hedgehog-1/nng-573371|archive-date=April 25, 2016|df=}}</ref> In 2005, it was [[Product bundling|compiled]] with ''ChuChu Rocket!'', ''[[Sonic Pinball Party]]'', and ''[[Sonic Battle]]'' in separate bundle packs for the GBA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Double Pack: Sonic Advance & ChuChu Rocket!|url=http://www.ign.com/games/double-pack-sonic-advance-chu-chu-rocket/gba-812527|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409104428/http://www.ign.com/games/double-pack-sonic-advance-chu-chu-rocket/gba-812527|archive-date=April 9, 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic Advance & Sonic Pinball Party Combo Pack|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-advance-sonic-pinball-party-combo-pack/gba-776209|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007082321/http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-advance-sonic-pinball-party-combo-pack/gba-776209|archive-date=October 7, 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2 Games in 1: Sonic Advance + Sonic Battle|url=https://www.gamespot.com/2-games-in-1-sonic-advance-sonic-battle/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312015017/http://www.gamespot.com/2-games-in-1-sonic-advance-sonic-battle/|archive-date=March 12, 2016|df=}}</ref> The game was released on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] on November 25, 2011, and on the [[Wii U]]'s [[Virtual Console]] on February 18, 2015. Both of these rereleases are exclusive to Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/11/26/sonic-advance-spin-dashes-to-android-in-japan/|title=Sonic Advance Spin-Dashes To Android In Japan|author1=Ishaan|first=|date=November 26, 2011|website=Siliconera|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69N8WLuto?url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/11/26/sonic-advance-spin-dashes-to-android-in-japan/|archive-date=July 23, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/02/gba_classics_sonic_advance_and_mega_man_and_bass_arrive_on_the_japanese_wii_u_eshop_next_week|title=GBA Classics Sonic Advance And Mega Man & Bass Arrive On The Japanese Wii U eShop Next Week|last1=Doolan|first1=Liam|date=February 10, 2015|website=Nintendo Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220150345/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/02/gba_classics_sonic_advance_and_mega_man_and_bass_arrive_on_the_japanese_wii_u_eshop_next_week|archive-date=December 20, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{video game reviews\n|MC = 87/100<ref name=\"mcgba\"/>\n|Allgame = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allgame\"/>\n|EGM = 7.8/10<ref name=\"egm\"/>\n|Fam = 32/40<ref>\"\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9 - \u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af \u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9\". [Game Boy Advance - Sonic Advance] ''Weekly Famitsu''. No.915 Pt.2. Pg.116. June 30, 2006.</ref>\n|GamePro = 17/20<ref name=\"GameProRev\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/e/ef/GamePro_US_162.pdf |title=Pro Reviews: ''Sonic Advance'' |author=Star Dingo |date=March 2002 |magazine=[[GamePro]] |page=68}}</ref>\n|GSpot = 7.9/10<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n|IGN = 9.1/10<ref name=\"ignrev\"/>\n|NLife = {{Rating|8|10}}<ref name=\"nlife\">{{cite web|last1=O'Neil|first1=James|title=Sonic Advance Review - GBA|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2011/06/sonic_advance_retro|website=Nintendo Life|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=November 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926205810/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2011/06/sonic_advance_retro|archive-date=September 26, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n|NWR = 8/10<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/>\n}}\n''Sonic Advance'' received \"generally favorable reviews\", according to review aggregation website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"mcgba\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/sonic-advance|title=Sonic Advance for Game Boy Advance|website=Metacritic|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69N8pxTSa?url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/sonic-advance|archive-date=July 23, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> The game sold 1.21 million copies in the United States, making it one of the [[List of best-selling Game Boy Advance video games|bestselling games for the GBA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|website=The Magic Box|accessdate=November 2, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421003854/http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|archivedate=April 21, 2007}}</ref> It earned $36 million by August 2006. During the period between January 2000 and August 2006, it was the 12th highest-selling game launched for the GBA, [[Nintendo DS]] or [[PlayStation Portable]] in the United States.<ref name=nextgensales>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010052300/http://www.next-gen.biz/index2.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3557&Itemid=2&pop=1&page=0 |url=http://www.next-gen.biz/index2.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3557&Itemid=2&pop=1&page=0 |title=The Century's Top 50 Handheld Games| author=Keiser, Joe | date=August 2, 2006 |work=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |archive-date=October 10, 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe game's presentation was well-received.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/><ref name=\"egm\"/> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' called ''Sonic Advance'' the best-looking 2D ''Sonic'' game.<ref name=\"egm\">{{cite journal|title=Sonic Advance Review|journal=Electronic Gaming Monthly|date=March 2002|page=146}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]'' praised its detailed scenery and animation, describing them as solid and faithful to the original Genesis games.<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-advance-review/1900-2846624/|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=February 8, 2002|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129022205/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-advance-review/1900-2846624/|archive-date=November 29, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''Nintendo World Report'' described its use of graphical techniques as elegant, praising its [[anime]]-inspired character animations, and compared them positively to the critically acclaimed [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] game ''[[Super Mario World]]'' (1990).<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> The game's music and audio was also praised;<ref name=\"ignrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/05/sonic-advance-review|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=February 5, 2002|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729100414/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/05/sonic-advance-review|archive-date=July 29, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''GameSpot'' called it comfortable and catchy.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/> Reviewers also praised the gameplay, with many comparing it favorably to the original games. ''[[IGN]]'' wrote the game's new ideas, such as the ability to grind on rails, were clever and determined that ''Sonic'' felt better on the GBA, rather than the Genesis.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> ''[[AllGame]]'' said the game relied too much on nostalgia, but felt it was still a \"winning formula\" and called the game enjoyable.<ref name=\"allgame\"/> The game's use of the GameCube link cable was praised; ''IGN'' noted the replay value and variety it offered,<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> and ''GameSpot'' called it interesting, and felt it made good use of the GBA's connectivity to the GameCube.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n\nCertain elements received more mixed responses.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/><ref name=\"allgame\"/> ''GameSpot'' felt that ''Sonic Advance'' lacked polish, and criticized the difficult special stages.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/> ''IGN''{{'}}s only criticism was the presence of problems from earlier titles, such as \"an inviting stretch of roadway that begs to have your character blaze across it at top speed, only to have a spike strip jab you in the feet somewhere in the middle\".<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> ''Nintendo World Report'' thought the game was too short and criticized the exclusion of the Super Sonic replay mode from earlier games.<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> Reviews for the N-Gage version were mixed; ''GameSpot'' criticized its choppy [[frame rate]] and encouraged readers to buy the superior GBA version instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonicn-review/1900-6085543/|title=SonicN Review|last1=Navarro|first1=Alex|date=December 12, 2003|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113063323/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonicn-review/1900-6085543/|archive-date=January 13, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''IGN'' agreed and felt the N-Gage's vertical screen and omission of the multiplayer modes had a negative impact on the ported version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/10/08/sonic-n-review|title=Sonic N Review|last1=Chambers|first1=Chadd|date=October 8, 2003|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730022634/http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/10/08/sonic-n-review|archive-date=July 30, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> Overall, reviewers felt ''Sonic Advance'' was a solid addition to the ''Sonic'' franchise. ''Nintendo World Report'' felt the game was not perfect, but was still a game that \"deserves a spot in your GBA case\".<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> ''IGN'' agreed, and stated the game successfully recaptured the spirit of classic ''Sonic'' gameplay while feeling unique and taking advantage of the GBA's capabilities.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2009, the ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' named ''Sonic Advance'' among the best games produced for a Nintendo platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/7356/features100-greatest-nintendo-games-the-complete-list/|title=100 Greatest Nintendo Games - The Complete List|last1=East|first1=Tom|date=March 3, 2009|website=Official Nintendo Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229210319/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/7356/features100-greatest-nintendo-games-the-complete-list/|archive-date=February 29, 2012|url-status=|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar]]'' called it the 13th best ''Sonic'' game in 2017.<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/> The same year, ''[[USgamer]]'' named it the sixth best, stating that while it did not feel like the classic Genesis games, its graphics were \"gorgeous\", which helped make the game a standout for the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|author1=USgamer Team|title=Gotta Go Fast: Ranking All of The Sonic The Hedgehog Games|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/gotta-go-fast-ranking-all-of-the-sonic-the-hedgehog-games|website=USgamer|accessdate=February 5, 2018|date=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Sonic Advance'' was the first ''Sonic'' game released for a Nintendo console.<ref name=\"says\"/><ref name=\"firstlook\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/17936/a-decade-of-pgcnwr-2001-the-year-in-review|title=2001: The Year in Review|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=March 9, 2009|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407013450/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/17936/a-decade-of-pgcnwr-2001-the-year-in-review|archive-date=April 7, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' considered this significant, as Nintendo and Sega were fierce rivals throughout the 1990s; ''Sonic Advance'' helped end this rivalry by \"reducing Sonic's die-hard brand loyalty to a distant memory from the halcyon-toned 1990s\".<ref name=\"gradarbest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/2/|title=The best Sonic games of all time|author1=GamesRadar Staff|first=|date=May 19, 2017|website=GamesRadar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930062254/http://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/2/|archive-date=September 30, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> The two companies would work closer together in the following years, collaborating for the first time in 2003 with ''[[F-Zero GX]]'' and, in 2007, both Sonic and Nintendo's mascot [[Mario]] would feature in ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/03/29/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games-interview|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Interview|last1=Burman|first1=Rob|date=March 29, 2007|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711204121/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/03/29/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games-interview|archive-date=July 11, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' wrote that Sonic\u2014created as opposition to Nintendo\u2014seemed at home on the company's consoles;<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Nintendo Power]] 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |pages=40, 41}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' agreed, saying Sonic and Nintendo were now \"like old friends\".<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/>\n\nThe game was also the first ''Sonic'' title developed by Dimps. Sega continued to contract the company in following years to create many games in the series. The first of these were two sequels to ''Sonic Advance''\u2014''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/03/14/sonic-advance-2-5|title=Sonic Advance 2|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=March 14, 2003|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813060716/http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/03/14/sonic-advance-2-5|archive-date=August 13, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' (2004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/27/sonic-advance-3|title=Sonic Advance 3|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=May 27, 2004|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313115515/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/27/sonic-advance-3|archive-date=March 13, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> Dimps also developed the [[Nintendo DS]] games ''[[Sonic Rush]]'' (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/11/11/sonic-rush|title=Sonic Rush|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=November 11, 2005|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816015149/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/11/11/sonic-rush|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Rush Adventure]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/17/sonic-rush-adventure-review|title=Sonic Rush Adventure Review|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=September 17, 2007|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005210142/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/17/sonic-rush-adventure-review|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> the handheld versions of ''[[Sonic Colors]]'' (2010),<ref name=\"gids\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_colors/b/nintendo_ds/archive/2010/11/09/sonic-colors-ds-review.aspx|title=Dimps Crafts Another Amazing 2D Sonic Game|last1=Turi|first1=Tim|date=November 9, 2010|website=Game Informer|publisher=GameStop|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67FIv0ZvE?url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_colors/b/nintendo_ds/archive/2010/11/09/sonic-colors-ds-review.aspx|archive-date=April 27, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Generations]]'' (2011),<ref name=\"gi3ds\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/3ds/archive/2011/11/22/sonic-generations-review-dimps-reliable-quality-skips-a-generation.aspx|title=Sonic Generations Review: Dimps\u2019 Reliable Quality Skips A Generation|last1=Turi|first1=Tim|date=November 22, 2011|website=Game Informer|publisher=GameStop|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401072330/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/3ds/archive/2011/11/22/sonic-generations-review-dimps-reliable-quality-skips-a-generation.aspx|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=October 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/10/interview_sega_on_bringing_sonic_lost_world_to_wii_u_and_3ds|title=Interview: SEGA On Bringing Sonic Lost World to Wii U and 3DS|last1=Whitehead|first1=Thomas|date=October 16, 2013|website=Nintendo Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324083748/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/10/interview_sega_on_bringing_sonic_lost_world_to_wii_u_and_3ds|archive-date=March 24, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and co-developed ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 4]]'' (2010) and the [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Wii]] versions of ''[[Sonic Unleashed]]'' (2008) with Sonic Team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Randy|title=Sega confirms Sonic 4 developed by Sonic Team and Dimps|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/18/sega-confirms-sonic-4-developed-by-sonic-team-and-dimps/|website=Engadget|accessdate=December 5, 2017|date=February 18, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205210051/https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/18/sega-confirms-sonic-4-developed-by-sonic-team-and-dimps/|archive-date=December 5, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/19/sonic-unleashed-review-3|title=Sonic Unleashed Review|last=Cassamassina|first=Matt|date=November 18, 2008|work=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712191359/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/19/sonic-unleashed-review-3|archive-date=July 12, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 17, 2017|df=}}</ref> Several journalists have noted that Dimps' handheld games have received consistently better reviews than Sonic Team's home console titles.<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sterling|first1=Jim|title=Review: Sonic Colors DS|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sonic-colors-ds-187744.phtml|website=Destructoid|accessdate=February 5, 2018|date=November 14, 2010}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' wrote this was because Dimps \"managed to keep the spirit\" of the original games alive in theirs.<ref name=\"riseandfall\">{{cite web|last1=Elston|first1=Brett|title=The rise, fall and deafening crash of Sonic the Hedgehog|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-rise-fall-and-deafening-crash-of-sonic-the-hedgehog/4/|website=GamesRadar|publisher=Future Publishing |accessdate=June 9, 2017|page=4|date=April 9, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018174852/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-rise-fall-and-deafening-crash-of-sonic-the-hedgehog/4/|archive-date=October 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA fanmade (and therefore free) remastered version is for PC, known as \"Sonic Advance Revamped\". The latest version as of March 2020 is the 2018 demo, which features 3 acts (the first two from the first stage, the third being the first act of the third stage), a default custom \"duo mode\" which allows the player to main one selected character while another follows, both of their own choice, and 3 new unlockable characters ([[Shadow the Hedgehog]], [[Cream the Rabbit]], and [[Blaze the Cat]]), each with their own animation sprites and gameplay styles just like the other characters. It is available [http://sonicfangameshq.com/forums/showcase/sonic-advance-revamped-demo-2-sage-2018.196/ here].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* {{Official website|http://sonic.sega.jp/advance/}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Dimps games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Advance games]]\n[[Category:N-Gage games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Sonic Team games]]\n[[Category:Sonic the Hedgehog video games]]\n[[Category:Sega video games]]\n[[Category:THQ games]]\n[[Category:Infogrames games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games for Wii U]]\n[[Category:Video games produced by Yuji Naka]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sonic Advance\n| image = Sonic Advance Coverart.png\n| alt = Cover art, depicting Sonic, Tails, Amy, Knuckles, and Chao. The game's logo is seen above all characters, and the Sega and Nintendo logos are seen in the right and left hand corners, respectively.\n| developer = [[Dimps]]<br/>[[Sonic Team]]\n| publisher = {{vgrelease|JP|[[Sega]]|NA|[[THQ]]|EU|[[Infogrames]]}}\n| series = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| platforms = [[Game Boy Advance]], [[N-Gage (device)|{{nowrap|N-Gage}}]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Mobile phone]]\n| released = '''Game Boy Advance'''{{vgrelease|JP|December 20, 2001|NA|February 3, 2002|PAL|March 8, 2002}}'''N-Gage'''{{vgrelease|WW|October 7, 2003}}'''Android'''{{vgrelease|JP|November 25, 2011}}'''J2ME'''{{vgrelease|WW|2011}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]], [[action game|action]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| director = Akinori Nishiyama\n| producer = [[Yuji Naka]]<br/>Hiroshi Matsumoto\n| artist = [[Yuji Uekawa]]\n| composer = [[Tatsuyuki Maeda]]<br/>Yutaka Minobe\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Sonic Advance'''''|\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9|Sonikku Adobansu|known as '''''SonicN''''' on the [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]]|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 2001 [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game]] developed by [[Dimps]] for the [[Game Boy Advance]] (GBA). It was the first ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' game to be released on a [[Nintendo]] platform and was produced in commemoration of the series' tenth anniversary. The story follows [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]], [[Tails (character)|Tails]], [[Knuckles the Echidna|Knuckles]], and [[Amy Rose|Amy]] as they journey to stop [[Doctor Eggman]] from taking over the world. Controlling a character, players are tasked with completing each [[Level (video gaming)|level]], defeating Eggman and his [[robot]] army, and collecting the seven [[Chaos Emeralds]].\n\nDevelopment began after [[Sega]] shifted its focus to third-party software development, due to the poor performance of the [[Dreamcast]] console. Sega recruited [[Dimps]] to lead development, making the game the first in the franchise developed by the studio. While ''Sonic Advance'' follows a similar style of gameplay to the [[Sega Genesis]] ''Sonic'' games, certain concepts and designs were reused from newer titles such as ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998). The game has been [[Porting|ported]] to [[Nokia]]'s [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices, and is available on the [[Wii U]] via the [[Virtual Console]] in Japan.\n\n''Sonic Advance'' received positive reviews for its graphics, character animations, and its similarities to the original Genesis games, but was criticized for its short length and special stages. It was a major commercial success, selling 1.21 million copies in the United States and is among the [[List of best-selling Game Boy Advance video games|GBA's bestselling titles]]. Dimps has since created many entries in the series, including two sequels to the game, ''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' (2002) and ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' (2004).\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:SonicAdvanceLoop.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Screenshot showing Sonic running around a loop in Angel Island zone, the game's fifth level. The HUD on the upper left-hand corner shows the timer, score, and amount of rings the player has.|Gameplay screenshot showing [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] in one of the game's levels]]\n''Sonic Advance'' is a [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game|platformer]] [[action game]] reminiscent of the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' games released for the [[Sega Genesis]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Players journey through an island to defeat [[Doctor Eggman]], who is attempting to capture its animal population to turn them into evil [[robot]]s. Players select one of four characters, each with their own unique set of moves. [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]] is fastest and can perform an \"insta-shield\" that protects him for a moment; [[Tails (character)|Tails]] can fly or swim for a short time; [[Knuckles the Echidna]] can glide through the air, swim above water for a few seconds and climb walls; and [[Amy Rose]] can destroy enemies using a hammer.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> Except for Amy, each character can defeat enemy robots by jumping and curling into a ball, or by performing a spin dash on the ground to gain speed. By entering a [[cheat code]], players can control Sonic while Tails runs alongside him, similar to ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2]]'' (1992).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Sonic Advance + Sonic Adventure 2 Battle Official Perfect Guide|last=|first=|publisher=Versus Books|year=2002|isbn=9780970646866|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe game takes place over six [[level (video gaming)|level]]s called zones. Each zone is split into two acts, where the player must guide their selected character past enemies and obstacles such as spikes and bottomless pits to reach the end in under ten minutes. Scattered around acts are springboards, boost pads, and golden [[Rings (Sonic the Hedgehog)|rings]], which serve as a form of [[Health (gaming)|health]]; players survive hits as long as they have at least one ring, but their rings will scatter and disappear after a short period.<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Players collect canisters that contain [[power-up]]s such as speed shoes, elemental shields, and [[invincibility]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The first act ends when players pass a signpost, and the second culminates in a [[boss fight]] with Eggman; after hitting him eight times, Eggman will flee and drop a capsule of captured animals. Each character starts the game with a number of lives, which are lost when they are hit with no rings in their possession, crushed, drown, or fall in a bottomless pit. If all lives are lost, they will receive a [[game over]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" />\n\nSpecial springs can be found near the top of certain acts.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> By jumping on them, the player can reach a special stage, where they are sent down a tube to collect rings. If they collect enough rings, the player receives a [[Chaos Emerald]].<ref name=\"gsrev\" /> Collecting all seven Emeralds unlocks an extra boss fight. The game also features a [[minigame]], Tiny Chao Garden, where players can raise [[Chao (Sonic)|Chao]].<ref name=\"nwrreview\" /> Players can transfer their Chao between the Tiny Chao Garden and the Chao Garden from the [[GameCube]] versions of ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' and ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]''.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> The game also features a competitive [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] mode, where up to four owners of the game can race to the end of a level or search for Chao.<ref name=\"nwrreview\" />\n\n==Development and release==\n[[File:Nintendo-Game-Boy-Advance-Purple-FL.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An indigo-colored Game Boy Advance (GBA), the handheld device Sonic Advance was developed for.|''Sonic Advance'' was developed for [[Nintendo]]'s [[Game Boy Advance]] handheld console]]\nIn January 2001, [[Sega]], facing financial troubles with the underperformance of its [[Dreamcast]] console, shifted from first to third-party software publishing,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sega-announces-drastic-restructuring/1100-2680518/|title=Sega announces drastic restructuring|last1=Ahmed|first1=Shahed|date=January 31, 2001|website=GameSpot|publisher=CBS Interactive|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704153502/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sega-announces-drastic-restructuring/1100-2680518/|archive-date=July 4, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> with [[Sony Computer Entertainment]]'s [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Nintendo]]'s [[Game Boy Advance]] (GBA) being primary focuses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/24/sega-confirms-ps2-and-game-boy-advance-negotiations|title=Sega Confirms PS2 and Game Boy Advance Negotiations|author1=IGN Staff|first=January 23, 2001|date=|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323144955/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/24/sega-confirms-ps2-and-game-boy-advance-negotiations|archive-date=March 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> A team of developers was formed to begin development on ''Sonic the Hedgehog Advance'' (later renamed ''Sonic Advance''), a ''Sonic'' title for the GBA that would commemorate the series' 10th anniversary.<ref name=\"says\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5068/sega-says|title=Sega Says...|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=January 31, 2001|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816040211/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5068/sega-says|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5572/sonic-team-shows-its-goods|title=Sonic Team shows its goods!|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=February 8, 2001|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816035052/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/5572/sonic-team-shows-its-goods|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> [[Dimps]], a studio formed by several former [[Neo Geo Pocket Color]] developers and funded by Sega, Sony, and [[Bandai]], developed the game with assistance from [[Sonic Team]].<ref name=\"igndimps\"/> Sonic Team conceived the game, but was understaffed on employees familiar with the GBA hardware and so recruited Dimps.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harris |first1=Craig |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/14/e3-2004-yuji-naka-talks-sonic |title=E3 2004: Yuji Naka Talks Sonic |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |date=May 13, 2004}}</ref> Several Dimps members worked on the critically acclaimed ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog Pocket Adventure]]'' (1999) for the Neo Geo Pocket Color.<ref name=\"igndimps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/04/18/gba-sonic-developed-by-dimps|title=GBA Sonic Developed By Dimps|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=April 18, 2001|website=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818082311/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/04/18/gba-sonic-developed-by-dimps|archive-date=August 18, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe developers decided to return to a gameplay style similar to the original Genesis ''Sonic'' games, which Naka felt was refreshing. Despite this, they also incorporated concepts from ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998) and [[Sonic Adventure 2|its 2001 sequel]], such as the ability to grind on rails and the modernized character designs by [[Yuji Uekawa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2001-first-impressions-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance/1100-2762273/|title=E3 2001: First Impressions: Sonic the Hedgehog Advance|last1=Ahmed|first1=Shahed|date=May 18, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923181118/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2001-first-impressions-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance/1100-2762273/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"allgame\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31757&tab=review|title=Sonic Advance - Review|last1=Miller|first1=Skyler|date=February 5, 2002|website=AllGame|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115083100/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31757&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|url-status=|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref> As the ''Sonic'' games released for the Dreamcast allowed players to download minigames onto the [[Visual Memory Unit]] (VMU), the development team decided to expand upon this by using a similar concept with the [[Nintendo GameCube \u2013 Game Boy Advance link cable|GameCube's GBA link cable]], making ''Sonic Advance'' one of the first games to use the cable.<ref name=\"tgs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tgs-2001-fall-sonic-advance-links-to-the-gamecube/1100-2817734/|title=TGS 2001 Fall: Sonic Advance links to the GameCube|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=October 15, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418103024/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/tgs-2001-fall-sonic-advance-links-to-the-gamecube/1100-2817734/|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> It also features graphical techniques such as rotation effects and [[Mode 7]].<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/>\n\nSega announced ''Sonic Advance'' and two other GBA titles on January 30, 2001.{{efn| The others were rereleases of ''[[ChuChu Rocket!]]'' (1999) and ''[[Puyo Puyo (video game)|Puyo Puyo]]'' (1991)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/31/sega-of-america-announces-three-for-game-boy-advance|title=Sega of America Announces Three for Game Boy Advance|author1=IGN Staff|first=|date=January 30, 2001|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809222222/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/01/31/sega-of-america-announces-three-for-game-boy-advance|archive-date=August 9, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> A video containing footage of the game's first level was featured at the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] (E3) in May 2001,<ref name=\"firstlook\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/05/18/e3-first-look-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance|title=E3: First Look: Sonic the Hedgehog Advance|author1=IGN Staff|first=May 18, 2001|date=|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818080300/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/05/18/e3-first-look-sonic-the-hedgehog-advance|archive-date=August 18, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> and [[game demo|demo]] versions were showcased at [[Nintendo Space World]] and the [[Tokyo Game Show]] later that year.<ref name=\"tgs\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/space-world-2001-hands-onsonic-advance/1100-2807904/|title=Space World 2001 Hands-on Sonic Advance|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=August 27, 2001|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923182155/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/space-world-2001-hands-onsonic-advance/1100-2807904/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> Sega released ''Sonic Advance'' in Japan on December 20, 2001,<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9|url=http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/gametitle/GameboyAdvance.html|website=Sonic Channel|trans-title=Game Boy Advance|publisher=Sega|accessdate=November 2, 2017|language=Japanese|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722111028/http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/gametitle/GameboyAdvance.html|archive-date=July 22, 2015|df=}}</ref> while [[THQ]] released it in North America on February 3, 2002. The game was released in Europe on March 8, 2003,<ref name=\"nwrreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/3858/sonic-advance-game-boy-advance|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=February 10, 2002|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816040942/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/3858/sonic-advance-game-boy-advance|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> where [[Infogrames]] handled marketing and distribution.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shannon |first1=Victoria |title=Infogrames Will Distribute Company's Games in Europe : Tech Brief:Sega Picks Partner |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/29/business/worldbusiness/IHT-infogrames-will-distribute-companys-games-in.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 18, 2019 |date=June 29, 2001}}</ref> A [[porting|port]] for [[Nokia]]'s [[N-Gage (device)|N-Gage]], ''SonicN'', was released worldwide on October 7, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=SonicN - N-Gage|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-the-hedgehog-1/nng-573371|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425185840/http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-the-hedgehog-1/nng-573371|archive-date=April 25, 2016|df=}}</ref> In 2005, it was [[Product bundling|compiled]] with ''ChuChu Rocket!'', ''[[Sonic Pinball Party]]'', and ''[[Sonic Battle]]'' in separate bundle packs for the GBA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Double Pack: Sonic Advance & ChuChu Rocket!|url=http://www.ign.com/games/double-pack-sonic-advance-chu-chu-rocket/gba-812527|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409104428/http://www.ign.com/games/double-pack-sonic-advance-chu-chu-rocket/gba-812527|archive-date=April 9, 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic Advance & Sonic Pinball Party Combo Pack|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-advance-sonic-pinball-party-combo-pack/gba-776209|website=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007082321/http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-advance-sonic-pinball-party-combo-pack/gba-776209|archive-date=October 7, 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2 Games in 1: Sonic Advance + Sonic Battle|url=https://www.gamespot.com/2-games-in-1-sonic-advance-sonic-battle/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=November 2, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312015017/http://www.gamespot.com/2-games-in-1-sonic-advance-sonic-battle/|archive-date=March 12, 2016|df=}}</ref> The game was released on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] on November 25, 2011, and on the [[Wii U]]'s [[Virtual Console]] on February 18, 2015. Both of these rereleases are exclusive to Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/11/26/sonic-advance-spin-dashes-to-android-in-japan/|title=Sonic Advance Spin-Dashes To Android In Japan|author1=Ishaan|first=|date=November 26, 2011|website=Siliconera|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69N8WLuto?url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/11/26/sonic-advance-spin-dashes-to-android-in-japan/|archive-date=July 23, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/02/gba_classics_sonic_advance_and_mega_man_and_bass_arrive_on_the_japanese_wii_u_eshop_next_week|title=GBA Classics Sonic Advance And Mega Man & Bass Arrive On The Japanese Wii U eShop Next Week|last1=Doolan|first1=Liam|date=February 10, 2015|website=Nintendo Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220150345/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/02/gba_classics_sonic_advance_and_mega_man_and_bass_arrive_on_the_japanese_wii_u_eshop_next_week|archive-date=December 20, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{video game reviews\n|MC = 87/100<ref name=\"mcgba\"/>\n|Allgame = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allgame\"/>\n|EGM = 7.8/10<ref name=\"egm\"/>\n|Fam = 32/40<ref>\"\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9 - \u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af \u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9\". [Game Boy Advance - Sonic Advance] ''Weekly Famitsu''. No.915 Pt.2. Pg.116. June 30, 2006.</ref>\n|GamePro = 17/20<ref name=\"GameProRev\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/e/ef/GamePro_US_162.pdf |title=Pro Reviews: ''Sonic Advance'' |author=Star Dingo |date=March 2002 |magazine=[[GamePro]] |page=68}}</ref>\n|GSpot = 7.9/10<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n|IGN = 9.1/10<ref name=\"ignrev\"/>\n|NLife = {{Rating|8|10}}<ref name=\"nlife\">{{cite web|last1=O'Neil|first1=James|title=Sonic Advance Review - GBA|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2011/06/sonic_advance_retro|website=Nintendo Life|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=November 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926205810/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2011/06/sonic_advance_retro|archive-date=September 26, 2017|df=}}</ref>\n|NWR = 8/10<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/>\n}}\n''Sonic Advance'' received \"generally favorable reviews\", according to review aggregation website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"mcgba\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/sonic-advance|title=Sonic Advance for Game Boy Advance|website=Metacritic|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69N8pxTSa?url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/sonic-advance|archive-date=July 23, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> The game sold 1.21 million copies in the United States, making it one of the [[List of best-selling Game Boy Advance video games|bestselling games for the GBA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|website=The Magic Box|accessdate=November 2, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421003854/http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|archivedate=April 21, 2007}}</ref> It earned $36 million by August 2006. During the period between January 2000 and August 2006, it was the 12th highest-selling game launched for the GBA, [[Nintendo DS]] or [[PlayStation Portable]] in the United States.<ref name=nextgensales>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010052300/http://www.next-gen.biz/index2.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3557&Itemid=2&pop=1&page=0 |url=http://www.next-gen.biz/index2.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3557&Itemid=2&pop=1&page=0 |title=The Century's Top 50 Handheld Games| author=Keiser, Joe | date=August 2, 2006 |work=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |archive-date=October 10, 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe game's presentation was well-received.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/><ref name=\"egm\"/> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' called ''Sonic Advance'' the best-looking 2D ''Sonic'' game.<ref name=\"egm\">{{cite journal|title=Sonic Advance Review|journal=Electronic Gaming Monthly|date=March 2002|page=146}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]'' praised its detailed scenery and animation, describing them as solid and faithful to the original Genesis games.<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-advance-review/1900-2846624/|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Torres|first1=Ricardo|date=February 8, 2002|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129022205/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-advance-review/1900-2846624/|archive-date=November 29, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''Nintendo World Report'' described its use of graphical techniques as elegant, praising its [[anime]]-inspired character animations, and compared them positively to the critically acclaimed [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] game ''[[Super Mario World]]'' (1990).<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> The game's music and audio was also praised;<ref name=\"ignrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/05/sonic-advance-review|title=Sonic Advance Review|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=February 5, 2002|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729100414/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/05/sonic-advance-review|archive-date=July 29, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''GameSpot'' called it comfortable and catchy.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/> Reviewers also praised the gameplay, with many comparing it favorably to the original games. ''[[IGN]]'' wrote the game's new ideas, such as the ability to grind on rails, were clever and determined that ''Sonic'' felt better on the GBA, rather than the Genesis.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> ''[[AllGame]]'' said the game relied too much on nostalgia, but felt it was still a \"winning formula\" and called the game enjoyable.<ref name=\"allgame\"/> The game's use of the GameCube link cable was praised; ''IGN'' noted the replay value and variety it offered,<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> and ''GameSpot'' called it interesting, and felt it made good use of the GBA's connectivity to the GameCube.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/>\n\nCertain elements received more mixed responses.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/><ref name=\"allgame\"/> ''GameSpot'' felt that ''Sonic Advance'' lacked polish, and criticized the difficult special stages.<ref name=\"gsrev\"/> ''IGN''{{'}}s only criticism was the presence of problems from earlier titles, such as \"an inviting stretch of roadway that begs to have your character blaze across it at top speed, only to have a spike strip jab you in the feet somewhere in the middle\".<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> ''Nintendo World Report'' thought the game was too short and criticized the exclusion of the Super Sonic replay mode from earlier games.<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> Reviews for the N-Gage version were mixed; ''GameSpot'' criticized its choppy [[frame rate]] and encouraged readers to buy the superior GBA version instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonicn-review/1900-6085543/|title=SonicN Review|last1=Navarro|first1=Alex|date=December 12, 2003|website=GameSpot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113063323/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonicn-review/1900-6085543/|archive-date=January 13, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''IGN'' agreed and felt the N-Gage's vertical screen and omission of the multiplayer modes had a negative impact on the ported version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/10/08/sonic-n-review|title=Sonic N Review|last1=Chambers|first1=Chadd|date=October 8, 2003|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730022634/http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/10/08/sonic-n-review|archive-date=July 30, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> Overall, reviewers felt ''Sonic Advance'' was a solid addition to the ''Sonic'' franchise. ''Nintendo World Report'' felt the game was not perfect, but was still a game that \"deserves a spot in your GBA case\".<ref name=\"nwrreview\"/> ''IGN'' agreed, and stated the game successfully recaptured the spirit of classic ''Sonic'' gameplay while feeling unique and taking advantage of the GBA's capabilities.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2009, the ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' named ''Sonic Advance'' among the best games produced for a Nintendo platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/7356/features100-greatest-nintendo-games-the-complete-list/|title=100 Greatest Nintendo Games - The Complete List|last1=East|first1=Tom|date=March 3, 2009|website=Official Nintendo Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229210319/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/7356/features100-greatest-nintendo-games-the-complete-list/|archive-date=February 29, 2012|url-status=|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar]]'' called it the 13th best ''Sonic'' game in 2017.<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/> The same year, ''[[USgamer]]'' named it the sixth best, stating that while it did not feel like the classic Genesis games, its graphics were \"gorgeous\", which helped make the game a standout for the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|author1=USgamer Team|title=Gotta Go Fast: Ranking All of The Sonic The Hedgehog Games|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/gotta-go-fast-ranking-all-of-the-sonic-the-hedgehog-games|website=USgamer|accessdate=February 5, 2018|date=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Sonic Advance'' was the first ''Sonic'' game released for a Nintendo console.<ref name=\"says\"/><ref name=\"firstlook\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/17936/a-decade-of-pgcnwr-2001-the-year-in-review|title=2001: The Year in Review|last1=Cole|first1=Michael|date=March 9, 2009|website=Nintendo World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407013450/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/17936/a-decade-of-pgcnwr-2001-the-year-in-review|archive-date=April 7, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 2, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' considered this significant, as Nintendo and Sega were fierce rivals throughout the 1990s; ''Sonic Advance'' helped end this rivalry by \"reducing Sonic's die-hard brand loyalty to a distant memory from the halcyon-toned 1990s\".<ref name=\"gradarbest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/2/|title=The best Sonic games of all time|author1=GamesRadar Staff|first=|date=May 19, 2017|website=GamesRadar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930062254/http://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/2/|archive-date=September 30, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> The two companies would work closer together in the following years, collaborating for the first time in 2003 with ''[[F-Zero GX]]'' and, in 2007, both Sonic and Nintendo's mascot [[Mario]] would feature in ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/03/29/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games-interview|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Interview|last1=Burman|first1=Rob|date=March 29, 2007|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711204121/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/03/29/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games-interview|archive-date=July 11, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' wrote that Sonic\u2014created as opposition to Nintendo\u2014seemed at home on the company's consoles;<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Nintendo Power]] 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |pages=40, 41}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' agreed, saying Sonic and Nintendo were now \"like old friends\".<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/>\n\nThe game was also the first ''Sonic'' title developed by Dimps. Sega continued to contract the company in following years to create many games in the series. The first of these were two sequels to ''Sonic Advance''\u2014''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/03/14/sonic-advance-2-5|title=Sonic Advance 2|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=March 14, 2003|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813060716/http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/03/14/sonic-advance-2-5|archive-date=August 13, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' (2004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/27/sonic-advance-3|title=Sonic Advance 3|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=May 27, 2004|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313115515/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/27/sonic-advance-3|archive-date=March 13, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> Dimps also developed the [[Nintendo DS]] games ''[[Sonic Rush]]'' (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/11/11/sonic-rush|title=Sonic Rush|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=November 11, 2005|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816015149/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/11/11/sonic-rush|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Rush Adventure]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/17/sonic-rush-adventure-review|title=Sonic Rush Adventure Review|last1=Harris|first1=Craig|date=September 17, 2007|website=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005210142/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/17/sonic-rush-adventure-review|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> the handheld versions of ''[[Sonic Colors]]'' (2010),<ref name=\"gids\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_colors/b/nintendo_ds/archive/2010/11/09/sonic-colors-ds-review.aspx|title=Dimps Crafts Another Amazing 2D Sonic Game|last1=Turi|first1=Tim|date=November 9, 2010|website=Game Informer|publisher=GameStop|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67FIv0ZvE?url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_colors/b/nintendo_ds/archive/2010/11/09/sonic-colors-ds-review.aspx|archive-date=April 27, 2012|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Generations]]'' (2011),<ref name=\"gi3ds\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/3ds/archive/2011/11/22/sonic-generations-review-dimps-reliable-quality-skips-a-generation.aspx|title=Sonic Generations Review: Dimps\u2019 Reliable Quality Skips A Generation|last1=Turi|first1=Tim|date=November 22, 2011|website=Game Informer|publisher=GameStop|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401072330/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/3ds/archive/2011/11/22/sonic-generations-review-dimps-reliable-quality-skips-a-generation.aspx|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=October 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/10/interview_sega_on_bringing_sonic_lost_world_to_wii_u_and_3ds|title=Interview: SEGA On Bringing Sonic Lost World to Wii U and 3DS|last1=Whitehead|first1=Thomas|date=October 16, 2013|website=Nintendo Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324083748/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/10/interview_sega_on_bringing_sonic_lost_world_to_wii_u_and_3ds|archive-date=March 24, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 3, 2017|df=}}</ref> and co-developed ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 4]]'' (2010) and the [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Wii]] versions of ''[[Sonic Unleashed]]'' (2008) with Sonic Team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Randy|title=Sega confirms Sonic 4 developed by Sonic Team and Dimps|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/18/sega-confirms-sonic-4-developed-by-sonic-team-and-dimps/|website=Engadget|accessdate=December 5, 2017|date=February 18, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205210051/https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/18/sega-confirms-sonic-4-developed-by-sonic-team-and-dimps/|archive-date=December 5, 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/19/sonic-unleashed-review-3|title=Sonic Unleashed Review|last=Cassamassina|first=Matt|date=November 18, 2008|work=IGN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712191359/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/19/sonic-unleashed-review-3|archive-date=July 12, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=November 17, 2017|df=}}</ref> Several journalists have noted that Dimps' handheld games have received consistently better reviews than Sonic Team's home console titles.<ref name=\"gradarbest\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sterling|first1=Jim|title=Review: Sonic Colors DS|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sonic-colors-ds-187744.phtml|website=Destructoid|accessdate=February 5, 2018|date=November 14, 2010}}</ref> ''GamesRadar'' wrote this was because Dimps \"managed to keep the spirit\" of the original games alive in theirs.<ref name=\"riseandfall\">{{cite web|last1=Elston|first1=Brett|title=The rise, fall and deafening crash of Sonic the Hedgehog|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-rise-fall-and-deafening-crash-of-sonic-the-hedgehog/4/|website=GamesRadar|publisher=Future Publishing |accessdate=June 9, 2017|page=4|date=April 9, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018174852/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-rise-fall-and-deafening-crash-of-sonic-the-hedgehog/4/|archive-date=October 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA free, remastered version is in the works for PC, known as \"Sonic Advance Revamped\". The latest version as of March 2020 is the 2018 demo, which features 3 acts (the first two from the first stage, the third being the first act of the third stage), a default custom \"duo mode\" which allows the player to main one selected character while another follows, both of their own choice, and 3 new unlockable characters ([[Shadow the Hedgehog]], [[Cream the Rabbit]], and [[Blaze the Cat]]), each with their own animation sprites and gameplay styles just like the other characters. It is available [http://sonicfangameshq.com/forums/showcase/sonic-advance-revamped-demo-2-sage-2018.196/ here].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* {{Official website|http://sonic.sega.jp/advance/}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Dimps games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Advance games]]\n[[Category:N-Gage games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Sonic Team games]]\n[[Category:Sonic the Hedgehog video games]]\n[[Category:Sega video games]]\n[[Category:THQ games]]\n[[Category:Infogrames games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games for Wii U]]\n[[Category:Video games produced by Yuji Naka]]\n", "name_user": "Xcalivyr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_Advance"}
{"title_page": "Henry Grier Bryant", "text_new": "[[File:HenryGrierBryant.jpg|thumb|Henry Grier Bryant]]\n'''Henry Grier Bryant''' (November 7, 1859 \u2013 December 7, 1932) was an American explorer and writer from [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania.\n\n==Education and early career==\nHenry Grier Bryant was born in [[Allegheny, Pennsylvania]] in 1859, the son of Walter Bryant, a successful lumber baron, and Eleanor Adams Henderson Bryant.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} The family moved to [[Philadelphia]] in 1866, where Bryant was educated in private schools.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] in New Hampshire from 1876 to 1879, then went to [[Princeton University]], where he graduated in 1883.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He earned a master's degree from the same school in 1886.{{sfn|Jordan|1921|p=219}} That same year, he earned an [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Jordan|1921|p=219}} Bryant worked for several years for the [[Edison Electric Light Company]], but spent much of his free time travelling in the western United States.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He never married.{{sfn|New York Times 1932}} His sister, Josephine, married [[P. Frederick Rothermel]], who was later district attorney of Philadelphia.{{sfn|New York Times 1929}}\n\n==Exploration==\n\n===Grand Falls===\n[[File:Grand Falls Labrador.jpg|thumb|Bryant explored Grand Falls, Labrador (now [[Churchill Falls]]) in 1891.]]\nIn 1891, Bryant became a member of the [[Geographical Society of Philadelphia]].{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} That same year, he organized an expedition to Grand Falls in Labrador, then a part of the [[Newfoundland Colony]] (now known as [[Churchill Falls]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], Canada.){{sfn|Williams|1933|p=247}} Although fur-trader [[John McLean (trader)|John McLean]] had been the first westerner to see the Falls in 1841, none were known to have returned since then.{{sfn|Marsh|2006}} The local [[Innu]] people had a taboo against visiting it.{{sfn|Marsh|2006}} Bryant had been fascinated with the Grand Falls for several years: \"There was something in the idea of this distant cataract\u2014thundering on for ages in that far-off land\u2014which appealed forcibly to one's imagination\".{{sfn|Bryant|1892|p=9}} Travelling up the [[Churchill River (Atlantic)|Grand River]] (now the Churchill River), Bryant's group encountered [[First Nations]] tribes that had very little contact with white society.{{sfn|Bryant|1892|pp=14\u201317}} After an arduous journey, they reached the Falls on September 2, 1891.{{sfn|Bryant|1892|p=30}} To that point, most knowledge of the Falls consisted of vague accounts by natives and McLean's journey of decades earlier; Bryant's detailed account of his trek was published in ''[[The Century Magazine]]'' in 1892, and attracted widespread attention.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} The Geographical Society of Philadelphia reprinted it in a book later that year.{{sfn|Bryant|1892}}\n\n===Mountaineering===\nAs Bryant was exploring the Grand Falls, another explorer, [[Robert Peary]], was [[Peary expedition to Greenland of 1891\u201392|travelling in Greenland]]. After Peary and his crew had not returned as expected, the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Philadelphia Academy of Natural Sciences]] organized a relief expedition led by [[Angelo Heilprin]], with Bryant as second-in-command.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} In 1894, Peary led a second attempt to explore the northern reaches of Greenland. Bryant served on the auxiliary crew, which traveled north from [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]], to bring the main party home, which they successfully accomplished.{{sfn|Bryant|1895|p=9}} His account of the trip was published in 1895.{{sfn|Bryant|1895}}\n\nBryant continued to explore the far north in 1897, when he organized and led and expedition to the area around [[Mount Saint Elias]] on the [[Alaska]]-[[Yukon Territory|Yukon]] border.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=82}} Two years later, he helped to finance [[George W. Melville]]'s study of oceanic currents in the polar regions.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} Bryant ventured south in 1904, visiting [[Popocat\u00e9petl]], a Mexican volcano, but returned to the north in 1907, when he crossed the [[Malaspina Glacier]], but was unsuccessful in summiting Mount Saint Elias.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} His mountaineering later took him to other peaks across the globe, including [[Mount Nantai]] in Japan, [[Pidurutalagala]] in Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), and [[Mauna Loa]] in Hawaii.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} He returned to Labrador in 1912 to explore the area around the [[Saint-Augustin River]].{{sfn|Bryant|1913|pp=1\u20132}} The following year, he was elected president of the [[Association of American Geographers]].{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=247}}\n\n==Death==\nBryant died in his home on December 7, 1932, after a brief illness.{{sfn|New York Times 1932}} He was buried in [[The Woodlands (Philadelphia)|Woodlands Cemetery]] in Philadelphia. The Philadelphia Geographical Society later established a gold medal in his honor, which has been awarded to [[John Oliver La Gorce]] in 1948 and [[Rachel Carson]] in 1952, among others.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist | colwidth = 26em | refs = }}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite news |title=P.F. Rothermel, Noted Lawyer, Dead|url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FB091EFA345A127A93C4AB178ED85F4D8285F9 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 26, 1929 |ref={{sfnRef|New York Times 1929}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=H.G. Bryant is Dead; Peary Arctic Aide|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F0DE0DF1E31E633A2575BC0A9649D946394D6CF |newspaper=The New York Times |date= December 8, 1932 |ref={{sfnRef|New York Times 1932}}}}\n*{{cite book | last = Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = A Journey to the Grand Falls of Labrador | publisher = Geographical Society of Philadelphia | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1892 | oclc = 8302962 | url = https://archive.org/stream/journeytograndfa00brya#page/n7/mode/2up | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = The Peary Auxiliary Expedition of 1894 | publisher = Geographical Society of Philadelphia | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1895 | oclc = 8302968 | url = http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/IPY/ipy_10_pdf/G742b911895.pdf | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite journal | last= Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = An Exploration in Southeastern Labrador | journal = The Bulletin of the Geographical Society of Philadelphia | date = January 1913 | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201315 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oNs2AAAAYAAJ& |ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Jordan | first = John W. | title = Encyclopedia of Pennsylvania Biography | volume = 13 | publisher = Lewis Historical Publishing Company | location = New York, New York | year = 1921 | oclc = 615509 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=xAI9AAAAYAAJ& | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia | last = Marsh | first = James | year = 2006 | article = Churchill Falls | encyclopedia =The Canadian Encyclopedia |url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/churchill-falls/ |ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book | last = Oberholtzer | first = Ellis Paxson | title = Philadelphia: a History of the City and its People | volume = IV | publisher = S.J. Clarke Publishing Company | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1912 | oclc = 1625418 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cjbABgAAQBAJ& | ref = harv }}\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1148 The Papers of Henry Grier Bryant] at Dartmouth College Library\n*{{cite journal | last= Williams | first = Frank E. | title = Henry Grier Bryant | journal = Annals of the Association of American Geographers | date = December 1933 | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 247\u2013250 | jstor = 2560611 |ref = harv | doi=10.1080/00045603309357076}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant, Henry Grier}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American explorers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:burials at The Woodlands Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy alumni]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:HenryGrierBryant.jpg|thumb|Henry Grier Bryant]]\n'''Henry Grier Bryant''' (November 7, 1859 \u2013 December 7, 1932) was an American explorer and writer from [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania.\n\n==Education and early career==\nHenry Grier Bryant was born in [[Allegheny, Pennsylvania]] in 1859, the son of Walter Bryant, a successful lumber baron, and Eleanor Adams Henderson Bryant.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} The family moved to [[Philadelphia]] in 1866, where Bryant was educated in private schools.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] in New Hampshire from 1876 to 1879, then went to [[Princeton University]], where he graduated in 1883.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He earned a master's degree from the same school in 1886.{{sfn|Jordan|1921|p=219}} That same year, he earned an [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Jordan|1921|p=219}} Bryant worked for several years for the [[Edison Electric Light Company]], but spent much of his free time travelling in the western United States.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} He never married.{{sfn|New York Times 1932}} His sister, Josephine, married [[P. Frederick Rothermel]], who was later district attorney of Philadelphia.{{sfn|New York Times 1929}}\n\n==Exploration==\n\n===Grand Falls===\n[[File:Grand Falls Labrador.jpg|thumb|Bryant explored Grand Falls, Labrador (now [[Churchill Falls]]) in 1891.]]\nIn 1891, Bryant became a member of the [[Geographical Society of Philadelphia]].{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} That same year, he organized an expedition to Grand Falls in Labrador, then a part of the [[Newfoundland Colony]] (now known as [[Churchill Falls]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], Canada.){{sfn|Williams|1933|p=247}} Although fur-trader [[John McLean (trader)|John McLean]] had been the first westerner to see the Falls in 1841, none were known to have returned since then.{{sfn|Marsh|2006}} The local [[Innu]] people had a taboo against visiting it.{{sfn|Marsh|2006}} Bryant had been fascinated with the Grand Falls for several years: \"There was something in the idea of this distant cataract\u2014thundering on for ages in that far-off land\u2014which appealed forcibly to one's imagination\".{{sfn|Bryant|1892|p=9}} Travelling up the [[Churchill River (Atlantic)|Grand River]] (now the Churchill River), Bryant's group encountered [[First Nations]] tribes that had very little contact with white society.{{sfn|Bryant|1892|pp=14\u201317}} After an arduous journey, they reached the Falls on September 2, 1891.{{sfn|Bryant|1892|p=30}} To that point, most knowledge of the Falls consisted of vague accounts by natives and McLean's journey of decades earlier; Bryant's detailed account of his trek was published in ''[[The Century Magazine]]'' in 1892, and attracted widespread attention.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} The Geographical Society of Philadelphia reprinted it in a book later that year.{{sfn|Bryant|1892}}\n\n===Mountaineering===\nAs Bryant was exploring the Grand Falls, another explorer, [[Robert Peary]], was [[Peary expedition to Greenland of 1891\u201392|travelling in Greenland]]. After Peary and his crew had not returned as expected, the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Philadelphia Academy of Natural Sciences]] organized a relief expedition led by [[Angelo Heilprin]], with Bryant as second-in-command.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=81}} In 1894, Peary led a second attempt to explore the northern reaches of Greenland. Bryant served on the auxiliary crew, which traveled north from [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]], to bring the main party home, which they successfully accomplished.{{sfn|Bryant|1895|p=9}} His account of the trip was published in 1895.{{sfn|Bryant|1895}}\n\nBryant continued to explore the far north in 1897, when he organized and led and expedition to the area around [[Mount Saint Elias]] on the [[Alaska]]-[[Yukon Territory|Yukon]] border.{{sfn|Oberholtzer|1912|p=82}} Two years later, he helped to finance [[George W. Melville]]'s study of oceanic currents in the polar regions.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} Bryant ventured south in 1904, visiting [[Popocat\u00e9petl]], a Mexican volcano, but returned to the north in 1907, when he crossed the [[Malaspina Glacier]], but was unsuccessful in summiting Mount Saint Elias.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} His mountaineering later took him to other peaks across the globe, including [[Mount Nantai]] in Japan, [[Pidurutalagala]] in Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), and [[Mauna Loa]] in Hawaii.{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=249}} He returned to Labrador in 1912 to explore the area around the [[Saint-Augustin River]].{{sfn|Bryant|1913|pp=1\u20132}} The following year, he was elected president of the [[Association of American Geographers]].{{sfn|Williams|1933|p=247}}\n\n==Death==\nBryant died in his home on December 7, 1932, after a brief illness.{{sfn|New York Times 1932}} He was buried in [[The Woodlands (Philadelphia)|Woodlands Cemetery]] in Philadelphia. The Philadelphia Geographical Society later established a gold medal in his honor, which has been awarded to [[John Oliver La Gorce]] in 1948 and [[Rachel Carson]] in 1952, among others.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist | colwidth = 26em | refs = }}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite news |title=P.F. Rothermel, Noted Lawyer, Dead|url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FB091EFA345A127A93C4AB178ED85F4D8285F9 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 26, 1929 |ref={{sfnRef|New York Times 1929}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=H.G. Bryant is Dead; Peary Arctic Aide|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F0DE0DF1E31E633A2575BC0A9649D946394D6CF |newspaper=The New York Times |date= December 8, 1932 |ref={{sfnRef|New York Times 1932}}}}\n*{{cite book | last = Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = A Journey to the Grand Falls of Labrador | publisher = Geographical Society of Philadelphia | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1892 | oclc = 8302962 | url = https://archive.org/stream/journeytograndfa00brya#page/n7/mode/2up | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = The Peary Auxiliary Expedition of 1894 | publisher = Geographical Society of Philadelphia | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1895 | oclc = 8302968 | url = http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/IPY/ipy_10_pdf/G742b911895.pdf | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite journal | last= Bryant | first = Henry Grier | title = An Exploration in Southeastern Labrador | journal = The Bulletin of the Geographical Society of Philadelphia | date = January 1913 | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201315 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oNs2AAAAYAAJ& |ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Jordan | first = John W. | title = Encyclopedia of Pennsylvania Biography | volume = 13 | publisher = Lewis Historical Publishing Company | location = New York, New York | year = 1921 | oclc = 615509 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=xAI9AAAAYAAJ& | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia | last = Marsh | first = James | year = 2006 | article = Churchill Falls | encyclopedia =The Canadian Encyclopedia |url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/churchill-falls/ |ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book | last = Oberholtzer | first = Ellis Paxson | title = Philadelphia: a History of the City and its People | volume = IV | publisher = S.J. Clarke Publishing Company | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | year = 1912 | oclc = 1625418 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cjbABgAAQBAJ& | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite journal | last= Williams | first = Frank E. | title = Henry Grier Bryant | journal = Annals of the Association of American Geographers | date = December 1933 | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 247\u2013250 | jstor = 2560611 |ref = harv | doi=10.1080/00045603309357076}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant, Henry Grier}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American explorers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:burials at The Woodlands Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Grier_Bryant"}
{"title_page": "Marcel Berthet", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Berthet-portrait-du-coureur-cycliste-sur-son-v\u00e9lo-2.jpeg\n| image_size     =\n|caption=Marcel Berthet in 1912\n|birth_date= 4 March 1888  \n|birth_place=[[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], France\n|death_date= 7 April 1953 (aged 65)\n|death_place= [[Rouen]], France\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=Cycling\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Marcel Berthet''' (4 March 1888 \u2013 7 April 1953) was a French cyclist who rode professionally between 1907 and 1923. He took part in the [[1908 Tour de France]], and set multiple records in one-hour ride in 1907, 1912 and 1913. He won the [[Six-day racing|six-day race]] of Brussels in 1921 and finished second in 1920. His brother Ernest Berthet was also a competitive cyclist.<ref name=r1/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=1976 Marcel Berthet]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berthet, Marcel}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Neuilly-sur-Seine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Berthet-portrait-du-coureur-cycliste-sur-son-v\u00e9lo-2.jpeg\n| image_size     =\n|caption=Marcel Berthet in 1912\n|birth_date= 4 March 1888  \n|birth_place=[[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], France\n|death_date= 7 April 1953 (aged 65)\n|death_place= [[Rouen]], France\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=Cycling\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Marcel Berthet''' (4 March 1888 \u2013 7 April 1953) was a French cyclist who rode professionally between 1907 and 1923. He took part in the [[1908 Tour de France]], and set multiple records in one-hour ride in 1907, 1912 and 1913. He won the [[Six-day racing|six-day race]] of Brussels in 1921 and finished second in 1920. His brother Ernest Berthet was also a competitive cyclist.<ref name=r1/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=1976 Marcel Berthet]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berthet, Marcel}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Neuilly-sur-Seine]]\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcel_Berthet"}
