orts-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/te/marc-texier-1.html |title=Marc Texier Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-05-06 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Texier, Marc}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Texier"}
{"title_page": "Marcel Dussault", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Marcel Dussault\n| image         = \n| fullname      = Marcel Dussault\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1926|03|14}}\n| birth_place   = [[La Ch\u00e2tre]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|9|19|1926|03|14}}\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Paris\u2013Bourges (2 times)\n}}\n'''Marcel Dussault''' (May 14, 1926 \u2013 September 19, 2014) was a [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racing|road racing cyclist]]. He won 21 races in a professional career that ran from 1948 to 1959. He won [[Paris\u2013Bourges]] in 1948 and 1949 and a stage in the [[1949 Tour de France]],<ref name=\"mdc1949\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=36\u00e8me Tour de France 1949|language=French|accessdate=8 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124102917/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|archivedate=24 January 2012}}</ref> wearing the yellow jersey as leader of the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]] the following day. He won another two Tour stages in 1950 and 1954.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lanouvellerepublique.fr/Indre/Communes/D%C3%A9ols/n/Contenus/Articles/2014/09/21/Marcel-Dussault-est-decede-2053240|title=Marcel Dussault est d\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9|publisher=lanouvellerepublique.fr|date=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1948\n:[[Paris\u2013Bourges]]\n;1949\n:[[Paris\u2013Bourges]]\n:Circuit des Deux Ponts\n:[[1949 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 1\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n;1950\n:[[1950 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n;1953\n:3rd stage [[Tour du Sud-Est]]\n;1954\n:[[1954 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 3\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/dussault_marcel.php Palmar\u00e8s of Marcel Dussault]\n*{{cycling archives|8425}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dussault, Marcel}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indre]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-1920s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Marcel Dussault\n| image         = \n| fullname      = Marcel Dussault\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1926|03|14}}\n| birth_place   = [[La Ch\u00e2tre]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|9|19|1926|03|14}}\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Paris\u2013Bourges (2 times)\n}}\n'''Marcel Dussault''' (May 14, 1926 \u2013 September 19, 2014) was a [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racing|road racing cyclist]]. He won 21 races in a professional career that ran from 1948 to 1959. He won [[Paris\u2013Bourges]] in 1948 and 1949 and a stage in the [[1949 Tour de France]],<ref name=\"mdc1949\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=36\u00e8me Tour de France 1949|language=French|accessdate=8 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124102917/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|archivedate=24 January 2012}}</ref> wearing the yellow jersey as leader of the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]] the following day. He won another two Tour stages in 1950 and 1954.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lanouvellerepublique.fr/Indre/Communes/D%C3%A9ols/n/Contenus/Articles/2014/09/21/Marcel-Dussault-est-decede-2053240|title=Marcel Dussault est d\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9|publisher=lanouvellerepublique.fr|date=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1948\n:[[Paris\u2013Bourges]]\n;1949\n:[[Paris\u2013Bourges]]\n:Circuit des Deux Ponts\n:[[1949 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 1\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n;1950\n:[[1950 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n;1953\n:3rd stage [[Tour du Sud-Est]]\n;1954\n:[[1954 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 3\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/dussault_marcel.php Palmar\u00e8s of Marcel Dussault]\n*{{cycling archives|8425}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dussault, Marcel}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indre]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcel_Dussault"}
